          <h2>China: Mentougou Landfill, Beijing, China</h2>
            
              <p><em>Background</em><br />
              Mentougou Landfill is a controlled-dumping  type of landfill owned and operated by the Mentougou District   Garbage Disposal   Center. The United States  Environmental Protection Agency (U.S. EPA) conducted a site assessment in early  2009. Later that year, a 65 kilowatt (kW) microturbine was installed to provide  power for onsite facilities. Construction of a comprehensive landfill gas  collection system is underway and there are plans to expand the electricity  generation capacity. The assessments are available in both <a href="../activities/actActivityDetailsForLandfill.aspx?myObjId=a07A000000D4HDnIAN&mySiteObjId=a09A00000098juWIAQ">English</a> and <a href="../activities/actActivityDetailsForLandfill.aspx?myObjId=a07A000000D4HDnIAN&mySiteObjId=a09A00000098juWIAQ">Chinese</a>.</p>
              <p><em>Future  gas production</em><br />
                The  landfill is expected to close in 2011 containing approximately 1.58 million tons  of waste. Preliminary biogas modeling estimates that 500 cubic meters per hour  of biogas at 50 percent methane with 65 percent collection efficiency can be  recovered for capture and use in 2010 (includes the amount used by the 65 kW  microturbine).</p>
              <p><em>Landfill management techniques</em><br />
                The  2009 site assessment determined that following best practice techniques at the  landfill could increase the efficiency of gas collection. These practices include  waste placement, proper compaction, regular cover, proper grading and drainage,  and effective leachate and gas recovery system installation.</p>
              <p><em>Emissions reductions</em><br />
                This  project has the potential to capture some, but not all, of its gas due to  design constraints. However, the potential for reducing methane emissions through  both capture and flaring could eliminate up to 395,021 metric  tons of carbon dioxide equivalent from 2010 to 2028.</p>
